**W2-D2-Multiple_Inheritance_Employee**
Goal: One child class can extend a parent further, adding its own extra attributes — this is how you'll model different user types (Admin/Company/Candidate) in your Project 1 later.

```python
class Employee:
    def __init__(self, name, salary):
        self.name = name
        self.salary = salary

    def info(self):
        print(f"{self.name} earns {self.salary}")

class Manager(Employee):
    def __init__(self, name, salary, team_size):
        super().__init__(name, salary)
        self.team_size = team_size

    def info(self):
        super().info()
        print(f"Manages a team of {self.team_size}")

class Developer(Employee):
    def __init__(self, name, salary, tech_stack):
        super().__init__(name, salary)
        self.tech_stack = tech_stack

    def info(self):
        super().info()
        print(f"Works with: {self.tech_stack}")

m1 = Manager("Ravi", 60000, 5)
d1 = Developer("Sai", 50000, "Python, Django")

m1.info()
d1.info()
```

`super()` is new here — it calls the parent's version of a method from inside the child. `super().__init__(name, salary)` means "let the parent set up name and salary, I'll just add my extra stuff on top." Without it, you'd have to rewrite `self.name = name` and `self.salary = salary` again in every child — repeating code inheritance is supposed to avoid.

Task: Create a third child `Intern(Employee)` with an extra attribute `mentor`. Override `info()` to call `super().info()` then print `f"Mentored by {self.mentor}"`.

Task: Add a method `give_raise(self, amount)` in the parent `Employee` class that adds `amount` to `self.salary`. Call it on a Manager and Developer object — confirm it works on both without being rewritten in either child.

Break it: Remove `super().__init__(name, salary)` from Manager's `__init__`, keep `self.team_size = team_size`. Try `m1.info()` — see it crash since `self.name` and `self.salary` were never actually set.

Real Coder Note: Always call `super().__init__()` first thing inside a child's `__init__` unless you have a specific reason not to — forgetting it is one of the most common inheritance bugs, and it fails silently until you try to use the missing attribute.

